  "market_context": "EUR/USD 5-minute chart on Fri 27 Jun '25, price oscillating around 1.1720-1.1730 after running lows. A new higher time frame candle opens and the analyst's indicator marks a gray T-spot zone where the wick high is expected to form.",
  "key_observation": "The anticipated highs the analyst viewed as failure swings were never swept, and the subsequent consolidation expanded away without retracing into the fair value gap, confirming that aggressive expansion produces very shallow or no retracements.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the gray box from the indicator marking where the wick high should form, expecting a short setup to develop.",
    "Step 2: Viewed all the prior highs as failure swings that needed to be swept before a valid short could be considered.",
    "Step 3: Observed that the sweep of those highs did not occur, so no short setup was taken.",
    "Step 4: After lows were run, watched for a shallow retracement into a fair value gap to potentially short the next leg.",
    "Step 5: Noted that price consolidated and expanded away from the FVG without retracing, again invalidating the setup.",
    "Step 6: On the new higher time frame candle open, looked for the wick to form in the T-spot zone with only a shallow retracement consistent with expansion conditions.",
    "Step 7: Concluded that since neither the required sweep nor the deep retracement occurred, the aggressive expansion confirmed shallow-or-no retracement behavior."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Not every anticipated setup materializes. When price expands aggressively, expect very shallow retracements or none at all; if the required liquidity sweep or FVG retrace does not occur, stand aside rather than force an entry.",
